[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Similar to Apple's HTTP Live Streaming (HLS) solution, MPEG-DASH works by breaking the content into a sequence of small segments, which are served over HTTP.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Each segment contains a short interval of playback time of content that is potentially many hours in duration, such as a movie or the live broadcast of a sport event.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] The content is made available at a variety of different bit rates, i.e., alternative segments encoded at different bit rates covering aligned short intervals of playback time.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] While the content is being played back by an MPEG-DASH client, the client uses a bit rate adaptation (ABR) algorithm to automatically select the segment with the highest bit rate possible that can be downloaded in time for playback without causing stalls or re-buffering events in the playback.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Thus, an MPEG-DASH client can seamlessly adapt to changing network conditions and provide high quality playback with few stalls or re-buffering events.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH is the first adaptive bit-rate HTTP-based streaming solution that is an international standard.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH should not be confused with a transport protocol — the transport protocol that MPEG-DASH uses depends on which version of HTTP is used: TCP is the transport over which HTTP and HTTP/2 run, while HTTP/3 runs over QUIC (which in turn runs over UDP).
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH uses existing HTTP web server infrastructure that is used for delivery of essentially all World Wide Web content.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] It allows devices like Internet-connected televisions, TV set-top boxes, desktop computers, smartphones, tablets, etc. to receive multimedia content (video, TV, radio, etc.) delivered via the Internet, coping with variable Internet receiving conditions.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Standardizing an adaptive streaming solution is meant to provide confidence to the market that the solution can be adopted for universal deployment, compared to similar but more proprietary solutions like Smooth Streaming by Microsoft, or HDS by Adobe.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Unlike HDS, or Smooth Streaming, DASH is codec-agnostic, which means it can use content encoded with any coding format, such as H.265, H.264, VP9, etc.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH technology was developed under MPEG.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Work on DASH started in 2010; it became a Draft International Standard in January 2011, and an International Standard in November 2011.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] The MPEG-DASH standard was published in April, 2012 but has been revised in 2019 and then once more in 2022 as [1].
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] DASH is a technology related to Adobe Systems HTTP Dynamic Streaming, Apple Inc.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] The DASH Industry Forum (DASH-IF) further promotes and catalyzes the adoption of MPEG-DASH and helps transition it from a specification into a real business.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] It consists of major streaming and media companies, including Microsoft, Netflix, Google, Ericsson, Samsung, Adobe, etc. and creates guidelines on the usage of DASH for different use cases in practice.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH is integrated in other standards, e.g.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH is supported in HbbTV (as of Version 1.5).
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] DASH is an adaptive bitrate streaming technology where a multimedia file is partitioned into one or more segments and delivered to a client using HTTP.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] A media presentation description (MPD) describes segment information (timing, URL, media characteristics like video resolution and bit rates), and can be organized in different ways such as SegmentList, SegmentTemplate, SegmentBase and SegmentTimeline, depending on the use case.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Segments can contain any media data, however the specification provides specific guidance and formats for use with two types of containers: ISO base media file format (e.g.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MP4 file format) or MPEG-2 Transport Stream.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] An early predecessor of DASH was an HTTP web server based streaming system called SProxy, developed and deployed in the Hewlett Packard Laboratories in 2006.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] DASH standard does not specify the adaptive bitrate streaming (ABR) logic.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] The current MPEG-DASH reference client dash.js offers both buffer-based (BOLA) and hybrid (DYNAMIC) bit rate adaptation algorithms.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] DASH is also agnostic to the underlying application layer protocol.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Thus, DASH can be used with other application protocols besides HTTP, e.g., DASH over CCN.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] On July 27, 2015, MPEG LA announced a call for MPEG-DASH-related patents in order to create a single patent pool for this technology.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG LA announced its MPEG-DASH patent portfolio licence.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-LA claims that the included patents are essential to the MPEG Dynamic Adaptive Streaming over HTTP standard.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] MPEG-DASH is available natively on Android through the ExoPlayer, on Samsung Smart TVs 2012+, LG Smart TV 2012+, Sony TV 2012+, Philips NetTV 4.1+, Panasonic Viera 2013+ and Chromecast.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] YouTube as well as Netflix already support MPEG-DASH, and different MPEG-DASH players are available.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] While MPEG-DASH isn't directly supported in HTML5, there are JavaScript implementations of MPEG-DASH which allow using MPEG-DASH in web browsers using the HTML5 Media Source Extensions (MSE).
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] There are also JavaScript implementations such as the bitdash player which support DRM for MPEG-DASH using the HTML5 Encrypted Media Extensions.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] In combination with WebGL, the HTML5-based adaptive bitrate streaming of MPEG-DASH enables also the efficient streaming of 360° video for live and on-demand use cases.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Note that no specific support is required from the server for DASH content, with the exception of Live Streaming.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Windows 10 used to have native support for DASH streaming in EdgeHTML, a proprietary browser engine that was used in Microsoft Edge (now referred to as Edge Legacy) before the transition to the Chromium-based Blink browser engine.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] Edge Legacy was included in Windows 10 up till version 2004.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] It was replaced by Edge Chromium in version 20H2.
[src:media-source-extensions/dynamic-adaptive-streaming-over-http] DASH support on other browsers & operating systems is available via Media Source Extensions.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] The **Media Source API**, formally known as **Media Source Extensions** (**MSE**), provides functionality enabling plugin-free web-based streaming media.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Using MSE, media streams can be created via JavaScript, and played using `<audio>` and `<video>` elements.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Playing video and audio has been available in web applications without plugins for a few years now, but the basic features offered have really only been useful for playing single whole tracks.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] We can't, for example, combine/split arraybuffers.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Streaming media has up until recently been the domain of Flash, with technologies like Flash Media Server serving video streams using the RTMP protocol.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] With Media Source Extensions (MSE), this is changing.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] MSE gives us finer-grained control over how much and how often content is fetched, and some control over memory usage details, such as when buffers are evicted.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] It lays the groundwork for adaptive bitrate streaming clients (such as those using DASH or HLS) to be built on its extensible API.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Creating assets that work with MSE in modern browsers is a laborious process, taking significant time, computing power, and energy.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] The usage of external utilities to massage the content into a suitable format is required.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] While browser support for the various media containers with MSE is spotty, usage of the H.264 video codec, AAC audio codec, and MP4 container format is a common baseline.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] MSE also provides an API for runtime detection of container and codec support.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] If you do not require explicit control of video quality over time, the rate at which content is fetched, or the rate at which memory is evicted, then the `<video>` and `<source>` tags may well be a simple and adequate solution.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Dynamic Adaptive Streaming over HTTP (DASH) is a protocol for specifying how adaptive content should be fetched.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] It is effectively a layer built on top of MSE for building adaptive bitrate streaming clients.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] While there are other protocols available (such as HTTP Live Streaming (HLS)), DASH has the most platform support.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] DASH moves lots of logic out of the network protocol and into the client side application logic, using the simpler HTTP protocol to fetch files.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Indeed, one can support DASH with a simple static file server, which is also great for CDNs.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] This is in direct contrast with previous streaming solutions that required expensive licenses for proprietary non-standard client/server protocol implementations.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] The two most common use cases for DASH involve watching content "on demand" or "live." On demand allows a developer to take their time transcoding the assets into multiple resolutions of various quality.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Live profile content can introduce latency due to its transcoding and broadcasting, so DASH is not suitable for real time communication like WebRTC is.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] It can however support significantly more client connections than WebRTC.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] There are numerous available free and open source tools for transcoding content and preparing it for use with DASH, DASH file servers, and DASH client libraries written in JavaScript.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] The DASH Adaptive Streaming for HTML video article provides an example of how to use DASH with MSE.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Starting with Chrome 108, MSE features are available in dedicated web workers, which allows for improved performance when manipulating `MediaSource`s and `SourceBuffer`s.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] To play back the media, the `MediaSource.handle` property is used to get a reference to a `MediaSourceHandle` object, a proxy for the `MediaSource` that can be transferred back to the main thread and attached to a media element via its `HTMLMediaElement.srcObject` property.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] See MSE-in-Workers Demo by Matt Wolenetz for a live example.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Represents a media source to be played via an `HTMLMediaElement` object.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] A proxy for a `MediaSource` that can be transferred from a dedicated worker back to the main thread and attached to a media element via its `HTMLMediaElement.srcObject` property.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Represents a chunk of media to be passed into an `HTMLMediaElement` via a `MediaSource` object.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] A simple container list for multiple `SourceBuffer` objects.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] A `MediaSource` that actively manages its memory content.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Unlike a regular `MediaSource`, a `ManagedMediaSource` can evict content from its source buffers at any time for reasons such as memory or hardware limitations.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] A `SourceBuffer` created by a `ManagedMediaSource`.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Fires `bufferedchange` events to notify the application when buffered ranges are modified, including when the user agent evicts content.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] The event object for the `bufferedchange` event, which contains `TimeRanges` representing the added and removed buffered ranges.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Contains information about the quality of video being played by a `<video>` element, such as number of dropped or corrupted frames.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Returned by the `HTMLVideoElement.getVideoPlaybackQuality()` method.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Returns a `TimeRanges` object that indicates the ranges of the media source that the browser has buffered (if any) at the moment the `buffered` property is accessed.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Returns a `TimeRanges` object that contains the time ranges that the user is able to seek to, if any.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] A media provider object representing the media resource to play or that has played in the current `HTMLMediaElement`, or `null` if not assigned.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Returns a `VideoPlaybackQuality` object for the currently played video.
[src:media-source-extensions/media-source-extensions-api] Returns the `SourceBuffer` that created the track in question.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] The **`SourceBuffer`** interface represents a chunk of media to be passed into an `HTMLMediaElement` and played, via a `MediaSource` object.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] This can be made up of one or several media segments.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Controls the timestamp for the end of the append window.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Controls the timestamp for the start of the append window.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] This is a timestamp range that can be used to filter what media data is appended to the `SourceBuffer`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Coded media frames with timestamps within this range will be appended, whereas those outside the range will be filtered out.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] A list of the audio tracks currently contained inside the `SourceBuffer`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Returns the time ranges that are currently buffered in the `SourceBuffer`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Controls how the order of media segments in the `SourceBuffer` is handled, in terms of whether they can be appended in any order, or they have to be kept in a strict sequence.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] A list of the text tracks currently contained inside the `SourceBuffer`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Controls the offset applied to timestamps inside media segments that are subsequently appended to the `SourceBuffer`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] A boolean indicating whether the `SourceBuffer` is currently being updated — i.e., whether an `appendBuffer()` or `remove()` operation is currently in progress.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] A list of the video tracks currently contained inside the `SourceBuffer`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Aborts the current segment and resets the segment parser.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Appends media segment data from an `ArrayBuffer`, a `TypedArray` or a `DataView` object to the `SourceBuffer`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Starts the process of asynchronously appending the specified buffer to the `SourceBuffer`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Returns a `Promise` which is fulfilled once the buffer has been appended.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Changes the MIME type that future calls to `appendBuffer()` will expect the new data to conform to.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Removes media segments within a specific time range from the `SourceBuffer`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Starts the process of asynchronously removing media segments in the specified range from the `SourceBuffer`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Returns a `Promise` which is fulfilled once all matching segments have been removed.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Fired when the buffer appending is aborted, because the `SourceBuffer.abort()` or `MediaSource.removeSourceBuffer()` method is called while the `SourceBuffer.appendBuffer()` algorithm is still running.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] `SourceBuffer.updating` changes from `true` to `false`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Fired when an error occurs during the processing of an `appendBuffer()` operation.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Fired whenever `SourceBuffer.appendBuffer()` or `SourceBuffer.remove()` completes.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Fired after the (not necessarily successful) completion of an `appendBuffer()` or `remove()` operation.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] This event is fired after the `update`, `error`, or `abort` events.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] Fired when an `appendBuffer()` or `remove()` operation begins.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] `updating` changes from `false` to `true`.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] The following example loads a video chunk by chunk as fast as possible, playing it as soon as it can.
[src:media-source-extensions/sourcebuffer] You can see the complete code at https://github.com/mdn/dom-examples/tree/main/sourcebuffer and try the demo live at https://mdn.github.io/dom-examples/sourcebuffer/.
